\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\f0\fs32\lang9 Abstract\par
\b0\fs22 Unmanned Ground Vehicles (UGVs) are becoming a crucial component of contemporary technology, with uses in fields like robotics, mapping, autonomous navigation, and environmental monitoring. The accurate integration of sensors, particularly LIDAR, is crucial for obstacle identification and navigation in order to improve their functionality. The design, development, and integration of a sturdy and lightweight mounting structure for LIDAR sensors on UGVs are the main objectives of this study. The main goals are to maximize coverage, optimize the sensor's field-of-view (FOV), and design a modular construction that can be used with different UGV platforms.\par
Using SolidWorks, three distinct mounting structure configurations were designed and evaluated at the start of the project. Every design was evaluated according to standards including structural stability, flexibility, and sensor coverage. To strike the ideal mix between durability and lightweight construction, the best design was chosen and constructed using aluminum profiles. The final construction satisfies the precision and robustness requirements while providing flexibility to support various sensor configurations for a range of FOV needs.\par
The manufactured structure's ability to improve the vehicle's operational efficiency was demonstrated through testing and successful integration with a UGV. The design's modularity makes it simple to reconfigure, which makes it appropriate for a variety of applications.\par
By offering a scalable and adaptable approach for sensor integration, this research makes a substantial addition to UGV technology. The study's findings ensure that UGVs can be adjusted to a range of operational situations and open the door for enhanced autonomous navigation and other sensor-driven applications. The design process, testing procedure, and performance evaluation are covered in more detail in later sections of the study.\par
