\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b\fs28 1.INTRODUCTION\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\fs22 According to the most expansive "dictionary" definition, an unmanned ground vehicle (UGV) is any piece of mechanical machinery that travels over the ground and is used for carrying or moving objects, but it specifically does not carry a person.  It takes some organizing concept to address such a vast universe of potential UGV systems, and in reality, a taxonomy of UGV systems might be based on any of the many attributes of each system.The academic community usually refers to UGVs (especially UGVs possessing significant autonomous capabilities) as mobile robots [1].\par
One of the key challenges in UGV design is developing sensor mounting systems that are both lightweight and structurally robust. The mounting structure must ensure that sensors are placed in a way that maximizes their coverage and efficiency while minimizing additional weight that could affect the vehicle's mobility [2]. Existing solutions often struggle to balance these factors, leading to either overly rigid mounts that limit flexibility or designs that compromise the vehicle's agility and sensor performance. Moreover, most systems do not allow for easy adaptation to different sensor types and UGV configurations, limiting their versatility in real-world applications [3].\par
This research is motivated by the need to design a modular and adaptable mounting structure that provides optimal sensor placement for LIDAR and other sensors, enhancing the operational capabilities of UGVs. In this study, the AgileX Ranger 4WS 4WD UGV, known for its versatility and robust performance, serves as the base platform for sensor integration. The LIDAR sensors used include the XT32, Falcon Kinetic, and FT120, each offering unique features that make them suitable for different autonomous navigation tasks. By utilizing SolidWorks for detailed 3D modeling and referring to sensor datasheets for accurate integration, this project aims to develop a flexible solution that can be adapted to various UGV platforms. Ultimately, the goal is to improve the adaptability, efficiency, and performance of autonomous systems, contributing to the advancement of robotics technologies and their real-world applications.\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\f1\fs32 2. Background\par
\fs22 2.1 Autonomous Ground Vehicles (UGVs)\par
\b0 A-UGV (A-unmanned ground vehicle) has been defined by ASTM Committee F45 [4] as an \ldblquote Automatic, Automated, or Autonomous vehicle that operates while in contact with the ground without a human operator\rdblquote , vehicle capable of following a pre programmed path and that does not deviate from the path without human intervention.\par
The AgileX Ranger 4WS 4WD is a widely used UGV model known for its versatility, durability, and four-wheel-drive capabilities. This model provides a stable platform for sensor integration, making it ideal for autonomous systems requiring precise control and movement in diverse environments. In this project, the AgileX Ranger 4WS 4WD served as the base platform for integrating and testing the mounting structure designed for LIDAR sensors [5].\par
