2.2.1 LIDAR Technology in Autonomous Systems\par
\b0\fs22 LIDAR technology works by emitting laser pulses and measuring the time it takes for the light to reflect back from objects in the environment[7]. This process allows LIDAR sensors to create high-resolution 3D point clouds of the surroundings, which are vital for mapping and obstacle detection. The XT32, Falcon Kinetic, and FT120 LIDAR sensors were selected for their high accuracy and ability to provide detailed environmental data, even in complex terrain. The correct positioning of these sensors is crucial to ensure that they cover the necessary area without interference. In this research, particular attention was given to designing a mounting structure that ensures optimal sensor alignment and maximum FOV, enabling the UGV to operate autonomously and effectively.\par
