\b\fs24 2.3 Sensor Mounting Systems in Robotics\par
\b0\fs22 In autonomous systems, attaching sensors\f2\emdash especially LIDAR\emdash is a major challenge. For the sensors to be properly aligned and stable across a range of operating circumstances, a sturdy and adaptable mounting solution is required. Additionally, mounting methods need to take climatic variables, sensor field-of-view, and vibration into consideration. The mounting mechanism for this project was made to support several sensor models, such as the FT120, Falcon Kinetic, and XT32 LIDARs, each of which has unique positioning needs. Because the sensor configuration may vary based on the particular mission or operating requirements, the framework also required to be flexible. For the frame, aluminum 30x30 T-slot rails were used because of their strength, adaptability, and simplicity of installation. \par
\b\f1\fs24 2.4 CAD Software and Prototyping in Robotics\par
\b0\fs22 Computer-Aided Design (CAD) software is an essential tool in the development of robotic systems. SolidWorks was used in this project to design the mounting structure, as it offers advanced features for modeling, simulation, and stress analysis. The 3D CAD models of the AgileX Ranger 4WS 4WD and the LIDAR sensors (XT32, Falcon Kinetic, and FT120) were used to evaluate the mounting points and assess the design's performance before physical fabrication. The simulation tools in SolidWorks enabled the testing of different mounting configurations and helped identify potential issues related to sensor alignment, stability, and field-of-view. Following the design phase, a prototype was fabricated using 30x30 aluminum T-slot rails, which are widely used in robotics for their versatility and strength. The T-slot rails allow for easy assembly and adjustments, making them an ideal choice for creating a modular and customizable mounting system.\par
