\b\fs32 3 Research Methodology\b0\fs22\par
The research methodology employed in this project focused on designing a robust and flexible mounting structure for LIDAR sensors to be integrated with unmanned ground vehicles (UGVs). The methodology consisted of several stages, including data acquisition, design, simulation, prototyping, and testing. Below is a detailed description of the key steps followed in the research process.\par
\b 3.1 Data Acquisition and Initial Design\b0\par
The initial phase involved obtaining 3D CAD designs for both the UGV and the LIDAR sensors from the manufacturer. This step was crucial as it allowed for precise measurements and alignment of the components, even though the physical parts were not available at the start of the project. By acquiring these designs, we were able to perform early-stage simulations and analyses within SolidWorks [8], a powerful CAD software used for modeling and simulations. These digital models were essential for carrying out virtual measurements and evaluating different mounting configurations without the need for immediate physical prototypes.\par
\par
